<!-- --></details></div></div></div></div><hr class="co-hairline"/></div><div><div id="post-479909" data-testid="post-body-479909" class="relative -top-20"></div><div class="co-post-header flex flex-row flex-wrap items-center gap-2 px-3 py-2"><div class="flex-0 mask relative aspect-square h-8 w-8  inline-block"><img src="https://staging.cohostcdn.org/avatar/16192-635b79a8-3faa-410b-86d4-15606e06a3bb-profile.png?dpr=2&amp;width=80&amp;height=80&amp;fit=cover&amp;auto=webp" class="mask mask-squircle h-full w-full object-cover" alt="garak"/></div><a href="https://cohost.org/garak" class="co-project-handle font-atkinson font-normal hover:underline">@<!-- -->garak<!-- --></a><time dateTime="2022-11-28T15:43:34.156Z" class="block flex-none text-xs tabular-nums text-gray-500" title="Mon, Nov 28, 2022, 3:43 PM"><a href="https://cohost.org/garak/post/479909-if-you-want-to-learn" class="hover:underline">11/28/2022, 3:43 PM</a></time></div><div><div><div class=" relative overflow-hidden supports-[overflow:clip]:overflow-clip isolate co-contain-paint" data-post-body="true" data-testid="post-body"><div class="co-prose prose my-4 overflow-hidden break-words px-3"><p>If you want to learn control flow that will thoroughly shake the foundations of how you think computers ought to work, then I recommend pointing your face in the direction of Prolog. It&#x27;s not so much a control flow operator (although &quot;cut&quot; <!-- --><code>!<!-- --></code> is certainly something), but rather how evaluation works in the whole language.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>In an imperative language, the three main operations are variable assignments, function calls, and sequencing. In Prolog, the two main operators are unification and backtracking. The equivalent of a function call establishes provisional values to variables. And then if that creates a problem, then the function unwinds the work it&#x27;s done and starts over with new values. I want to reinforce, this is not just a trick which can be used sometimes, this is the <!-- --><strong>primary control flow<!-- --></strong> for the language.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>As an example, let&#x27;s saying you write in Prolog the rules for checking a Sudoku solution. Your source code contains the rules, one by one, of what makes a solution correct. That&#x27;s all you do.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>That program is a Sudoku <!-- --><em>solver<!-- --></em>. The solving happens just by calling the function you defined with some values unassigned, and the semantics of Prolog are to fill it in with a valid solution. (The strategy it uses for doing so depends on <!-- --><em>how<!-- --></em> you specify the rules.)<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>One of my favorite things about Prolog is that normal languages you need to define separate &quot;print&quot; and &quot;parse&quot; methods but in Prolog you can sometimes get away with just one function that can do either. You define a correspondence between data and a string. You can print by calling that function with data but no string, and it fills in the string; and you can parse by calling it with a string but not data, and it fills in the data.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>In practice, Prolog tends to be used in very small amounts in large systems. There are some tasks where a few dozen lines of Prolog can replace <!-- --><em>thousands<!-- --></em> of lines of imperative code; and that&#x27;s the only situation where the complexity is worthwhile. To my understanding, the Windows kernel uses Prolog for its network filtering rules, which is in the same ballpark as a Sudoku solver.<!-- --></p></div></div></div></div></div><hr class="co-hairline"/><footer class="co-thread-footer w-full max-w-full rounded-b-lg p-3"><div class="flex justify-between align-middle"><div class="w-max flex-none"><a href="https://cohost.org/garak/post/479909-if-you-want-to-learn#comments" class="text-sm hover:underline">8 comments<!-- --> + 39 on shared posts<!-- --></a></div><div class="flex items-center justify-end gap-3"><a href="https://cohost.org/Corncycle/post/compose?shareOfPostId=479909" title="share this post as Corncycle"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-width="1.5" stroke="currentColor" aria-hidden="true" class="h-6 w-6 co-action-button "><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M16.023 9.348h4.992v-.001M2.985 19.644v-4.992m0 0h4.992m-4.993 0l3.181 3.183a8.25 8.25 0 0013.803-3.7M4.031 9.865a8.25 8.25 0 0113.803-3.7l3.181 3.182m0-4.991v4.99"></path></svg></a><button class="w-6 h-6 pointer relative" title="unlike this post as Corncycle"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor" aria-hidden="true" class="w-6 h-6 pointer absolute top-0 left-0 text-cherry visible"><path d="M11.645 20.91l-.007-.003-.022-.012a15.247 15.247 0 01-.383-.218 25.18 25.18 0 01-4.244-3.17C4.688 15.36 2.25 12.174 2.25 8.25 2.25 5.322 4.714 3 7.688 3A5.5 5.5 0 0112 5.052 5.5 5.5 0 0116.313 3c2.973 0 5.437 2.322 5.437 5.25 0 3.925-2.438 7.111-4.739 9.256a25.175 25.175 0 01-4.244 3.17 15.247 15.247 0 01-.383.219l-.022.012-.007.004-.003.001a.752.752 0 01-.704 0l-.003-.001z"></pat