ask relative aspect-square h-8 w-8 lg:hidden inline-block"><img src="https://staging.cohostcdn.org/avatar/8982-4dbbb6db-4980-4a57-bbeb-415f82d1b551-profile.jpg?dpr=2&amp;width=80&amp;height=80&amp;fit=cover&amp;auto=webp" class="mask mask-roundrect h-full w-full object-cover" alt="fizbin"/></div><a rel="author" href="https://cohost.org/fizbin" class="co-project-display-name max-w-full flex-shrink truncate font-atkinson font-bold hover:underline" title="Daniel Martin">Daniel Martin</a><a href="https://cohost.org/fizbin" class="co-project-handle font-atkinson font-normal hover:underline">@<!-- -->fizbin<!-- --></a><time dateTime="2022-11-29T14:11:13.767Z" class="block flex-none text-xs tabular-nums text-gray-500" title="Tue, Nov 29, 2022, 2:11 PM"><a href="#comment-0645722e-5658-46ab-9029-e99d5a28c219" class="hover:underline">11/29/2022, 2:11 PM</a></time></div><div class="co-prose prose overflow-hidden break-words"><p>The way I think of the &quot;else&quot; bit in <!-- --><code>for<!-- --></code>...<!-- --><code>else<!-- --></code> is that in your loop you&#x27;re going to guard the <!-- --><code>break<!-- --></code> or <!-- --><code>return<!-- --></code> statements with some sort of conditional, so you have a loop like this:<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><pre><code>for x in thingy:
