"flex min-w-0 flex-1 flex-col justify-start gap-2"><div class="flex flex-row flex-wrap items-center gap-2"><div class="flex-0 mask relative aspect-square h-8 w-8 lg:hidden inline-block"><img src="https://staging.cohostcdn.org/avatar/77167-cb26a4fd-da9b-48e8-b8dd-b6a70a31c8ff-profile.png?dpr=2&amp;width=80&amp;height=80&amp;fit=cover&amp;auto=webp" class="mask mask-roundrect h-full w-full object-cover" alt="olus2000"/></div><a href="https://cohost.org/olus2000" class="co-project-handle font-atkinson font-normal hover:underline">@<!-- -->olus2000<!-- --></a><time dateTime="2022-11-29T14:36:38.310Z" class="block flex-none text-xs tabular-nums text-gray-500" title="Tue, Nov 29, 2022, 2:36 PM"><a href="#comment-3ffca7b5-fe3a-406d-b02c-21da9d46740c" class="hover:underline">11/29/2022, 2:36 PM</a></time></div><div class="co-prose prose overflow-hidden break-words"><p>My personal favorite is a concatenative-style while. It comes in many flavors, but the important part is that unlike C-style <!-- --><code>while () {}<!-- --></code> or <!-- --><code>do {} while ()<!-- --></code> you can have logic both before <!-- --><em>and<!-- --></em> after the predicate check. This is similar in spirit to <!-- --><code>break<!-- --></code>, but still only allows a single breakpoint in the loop which helps visibility, and actually allows rewriting many <!-- --><code>break<!-- --></code> usecases without the problematic keyword. No matter if its Factor&#x27;s <!-- --><code>[ pred ] [ body ] while<!-- --></code> or Forth&#x27;s <!-- --><code>BEGIN pred WHILE body REPEAT<!-- --></code> or even Quackery&#x27;s <!-- --><code>[ pred while body again ]<!-- --></code>.<!-- --></p></div><div class="flex flex-row items-center gap-2"><button class="co-link-button flex cursor-pointer flex-row 
